<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>Motivation</h3>

<p>This work was done to help product designers understand on an aggregate level how users interact with our web offering: what opportunities there are for educating users, encouraging commercial behavior, and avoiding confusion about what to do next. Hi.</p>
 </div>



<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>The data</h3>

<p>Pageview data over the last two days (218k pageviews), with aggregated pagetypes as defined by <a href="https://github.com/artsy/fulcrum/blob/master/lib/fulcrum/transform/pagetypes.rb">fulcrum</a> (e.g. /artist/andy-warhol becomes pagetype &#39;artist&#39;). We join the pageview data to a table which joins inquiries to the page before the inquiry occurred.</p>
 </div>

<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>Inquiring visitors to the Artist page show a promising pattern of behavior</h3>

<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <p>A user starts on the artist page (far left), and then the majority move immediately to an artwork page (up and to the right), and then inquire there. A good number also move back to an artist, and then to an artwork, and so on.  We posit that this behavior is ideal for commercial interaction, and we&#39;ll come back to this thought.</p>

<p><strong>&quot;Other&quot;</strong> can be any of a number of pages, including artsy.net/artworks, artsy.net/collect, etc.  In this case, since users are inquiring on these pages we know that they are artsy.net/inquire, which is a page unique to mobile web. This means a few pageviews from mobile are sneaking into our analysis, which is something that should be addressed in future work.</p>
 </div>

<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>Different starting points leads to very different patterns of usage</h3>

<p>This is limiting to 14,000 random users, and turning down the alpha (making it more transparent) so that the patterns are clearly visible.</p>

<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <p>The most salient features of these graphs are the patterns visible, of which there are three main types:</p>

<p>1) <strong>Article readers&#39;</strong> second pageview is extremely likely to be an article (if they have a second pageview at all).  They mostly do not visit other parts of the site, and if they do they tend not to stay long.  We know from other research that article readers rarely inquire, so this siloed behavior makes sense.</p>

<p>2) <strong>Artist viewers&#39;</strong> second pageview is extremely likely to be another artist or an artwork, after which they exhibit a behavior of bouncing back and forth between artist and artwork pages (perhaps by clicking the back button after viewing each artwork-- there&#39;s more work to be done here).  These viewers are much more likely than article readers to inquire.  <strong>Artwork</strong> viewers tend, on the other hand, to inquire immediately after landing on an artwork, and do little else-- these are high intent users who know what they&#39;re looking for.</p>

<p>3) <strong>Homepage viewers</strong> exhibit a fairly diverse range of next steps, with the bulk of their attention going to pages which don&#39;t make the top 5: collect, search, etc.  The subset who do go to search or collect, however, fall into a familiar pattern. We dive into this below.</p>
 </div>



<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>Recap / Next steps</h3>

<p>There&#39;s much room for further analysis using this kind of visualization of user paths. Below I present a few options, but I expect this list isn&#39;t exhaustive.</p>
 </div>

<div class='cell cell-content-markdown'> <h3>Deeper dive into the Homepage</h3>

<p>The home page generates the most diversity of user behavior of any of the top five pagetypes. Here, we see a subset of users do go from the home page to an artwork or artist and engage in the browsing pattern we saw above, either directly or from the search or collect page.</p>

<p>Logged in users go to works-for-you, the auctions page (not a specific auction), while logged out users use collect much more heavily. Both use search quite a bit.</p>
